What is a LinkedHashMap?
LinkedHashMap is a part of the Java Collections Framework that extends HashMap while maintaining insertion order.
It stores key-value pairs like HashMap, but it also maintains a linked list of entries to preserve the order
in which keys are inserted.
What are the Key Characteristics of LinkedHashMap?
âœ… Maintains Insertion Order â€“ Unlike HashMap, it remembers the order in which elements were added.
âœ… Faster Access (O(1)) â€“ Similar performance to HashMap.
âœ… Allows null Keys and Values â€“ Just like HashMap, it allows one null key and multiple null values.
âœ… Not Thread-Safe â€“ Needs external synchronization for multi-threaded access.
âœ… Provides Access Order Mode â€“ Can be configured to maintain access order (useful for LRU caches).


How is the Internal Working of LinkedHashMap?
â— Uses a combination of a Hash Table and a Doubly Linked List.
â— Each entry contains pointers to previous and next elements, forming a linked list.
â— When an entry is added, it is linked to the previous entry in insertion order.
â— Access Order Mode (accessOrder = true) allows the most recently accessed elements to move to the end (used for implementing LRU caches).

When to Use LinkedHashMap?
âœ” When insertion order matters
âœ” When you need an LRU cache implementation
âŒ Avoid if ordering is not needed (use HashMap instead for better performance).

What is LRU?
LRU (Least Recently Used) Cache is a caching algorithm that removes the least recently used items when the cache reaches its capacity.
âœ” Efficiently manages memory usage
âœ” Ensures frequently used items stay in cache
âœ” Used in databases, operating systems, and web caching

How Does LRU Work?
â— The cache has a fixed size.
â— When a new item is accessed, it is moved to the most recently used position.
â— If an item is accessed again, it moves to the front.
â— When the cache is full, the least recently used item (at the back) is removed to make space for a new entry.
ğŸ”¹ Think of it like a queue where the most recently used elements stay in front!
What are the Real-World Examples of LRU?
ğŸ”¹ Web Browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, etc.)
â— The browser caches recently visited web pages.
â— If cache memory is full, older pages (least accessed) are removed first.
ğŸ”¹ Operating Systems
â— OS manages memory using LRU in page replacement algorithms.
â— When RAM is full, the least used pages are swapped out.
ğŸ”¹ Database Systems
â— Databases use LRU for query caching to optimize repeated queries.